\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Assignment 7 Problem 4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Michael Cai
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
4.
 Two people walk along different paths starting at the origin, such that
 they have the same positive x-coordinate at each time.
 One follows the positive x-axis, while the other follows the curve 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\frac{2}{3}x^{\frac{3}{2}}.$
\end_inset

 Find the point at which one person has walked twice as far as the other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Again, we use the arc length formula to measure the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

distance traveled
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by the person walking along the arc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $y=\frac{2}{3}x^{\frac{3}{2}}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $y'=x^{\frac{1}{2}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $(y')^{2}=x$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $L=\int_{0}^{b}\sqrt{1+x}dx$
\end_inset

 , where 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 indicates the x-coordinate that the person walking along the arc is currently
 on.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $u=1+x,$
\end_inset

 thus 
\begin_inset Formula $du=dx$
\end_inset

, and the limits equal 
\begin_inset Formula $ulim=b+1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $llim=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $=\int_{1}^{b+1}u^{\frac{1}{2}}du$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $=[\frac{2}{3}u^{\frac{3}{2}}]\bigg|_{1}^{b+1}=\frac{2}{3}(b+1)^{\frac{3}{2}}-\frac{2}{3}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We know that the distance of the man walking along the x-axis is just going
 to be x, whereas the distance for the man walking along the arc is going
 to be given by the formula I just derived.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because an arc will always be longer than an x-value at a given point x
 (we know this if we approximate an arc to be a straight line, then the
 hypotenuse would represent that straightened arc and the bottom edge of
 the triangle would represent the x-axis), we know that the man walking
 along the arc will always be ahead of the man walking along the x-axis
 at points 
\begin_inset Formula $x>0.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus we must calculate the point in time when the arc man is twice as far
 as the x-axis man.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2}{3}(b+1)^{\frac{2}{3}}-\frac{2}{3}=2b$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{3}(b+1)^{\frac{2}{3}}-\frac{1}{3}=b$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_body
